T1  - Transitory variation in investment and output
AU  - Fama, Eugene F.
JO  - Journal of Monetary Economics
VL  - 30
IS  - 3
SP  - 467
EP  - 480
PY  - 1992
DA  - 1992/12/01/
SN  - 0304-3932
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3932(92)90007-O
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030439329290007O
AB  - Although the permanent-income model is a cornerstone of macreoconomics, the evidence for its assumption that output has a transitory component is mixed. This paper documents transitory variation in GNP. The story centers on the variation in investment, relative to consumption. Consumption behaves like a random walk. In the long term, investment moves one-for-one with consumption. In the near term, however, investment takes strong transitory swings away from the random walk it shares with consumption. These surges in investment, relative to consumption, are not offset by Government Expenditures. Transitory variation in investment thus becomes transitory variation in GNP.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Does the debt market assess large banks, risk?: Time series evidence from money center CDs
AU  - Ellis, David M.
AU  - Flannery, Mark J.
JO  - Journal of Monetary Economics
VL  - 30
IS  - 3
SP  - 481
EP  - 502
PY  - 1992
DA  - 1992/12/01/
SN  - 0304-3932
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3932(92)90008-P
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030439329290008P
AB  - Uninsured bank liabilities should offer a promised yield that compensates depositors for their expected default losses. However, the conjectural, guarantees available to large U.S. banking firms makes it questionable whether large depositors should or do feel themselves exposed to credit risk. Prior papers have evaluated the determinants of bank risk premia using cross-sectional data, with relatively inconclusive results. This paper investigates the same issue in a methodologically independent fashion: using time series data on specific banks' daily offering rates during the period May 1982 through July 1988. We find that CD rates paid by large money center banks include significant default risk premia.
